Regarding issue #1057, this is a proposed solution that generates all the permutations needed to mix any grid size _n_ with any column spanning (up to _n_).  (See codepen [with](http://codepen.io/MrFusion42/pen/wBLKQj) and [without](http://codepen.io/MrFusion42/pen/emajvo) this patch)

As a side-effect of this new feature, the generation of all other column-related rules is now automated (so for example setting `@columnCount: 18` generates the `.seventeen` and `.eighteen` classes and rules on forms and tables).

Generating rules for _n_ columns is as easy as:

``` less
&{.forCols(); .-each(@number, @i) {
    .my.@{number}.column.grid > .foo.column {
        .-nColumn
    }
}}
```

This generates:

``` css
.my.one.column.grid > .foo.column {
    width: 100%;
}
.my.two.column.grid > .foo.column {
    width: 50%;
}
.my.three.column.grid > .foo.column {
    width: 33.33333333%;
}

/* ... up to @columnCount, or pass a number to .forCols() */

.my.n-th.column.grid > .foo.column {
    width: 5%;
}
```

I documented the generators on `mixins.less`, but I guess that should go elsewhere.

If this PR is too disruptive, I can create a new one that just adds the needed rules to `grid.less` :smile:

